comment: Material settings for both inks changed: projection delay 0.5 -> 1. Global offset is 0.5. Vol. T1: 200 µL (layer 1). Vol. T2: 100 µL (layer 2). Printed layers look too thin (especially 1st GelMA base layer), HAMA channels very shallow and not printed completely at the side of construct. It appears that global offset of 0.5 (worked well on 220114) is not enough today. Construct collected for analysis.

Vol. T1: Rest #1 +200 µL (layer 1). Vol. T2: 100 µL (layer 2). Printed layers look a bit too thick. HAMA channels disturbed partly: might have flapped over to to high channel height-to-width ratio as global offset might be too much. Construct collected for analysis.
next steps: Removing, cleaning and putting back both ink vats. Setting global offset to 0.7.

comment: Vol. T1: 200 µL (layer 1). Vol. T2: 100 µL (layer 2). Printed GelMA layer too thin, similar to run #1, although offset is 0.2 higher! -> Removed and cleaned ink vats seem to have not exact same placement on printer, although they are the same.
Vol. T1: +100 µL (layer 1). Height of GelMA base layer seems fine.

Vol. T1: +100 µL (layer 1). Vol. T3: 100 µL (layer 2). Height of GelMA base layer seems fine. HAMA ink only covers ca. 40% of layer 1 due to misplacement -> only channels on one side. Printed HAMA channels very faintly visible, seem ill-printed -> exposure time might be too short
next steps: Increase T3 exposure time 15 s -> 25 s.

comment: Vol. T1: +100 µL (layer 1). Vol. T3: 100 µL (layer 2). HAMA channels well visible, but many are not straight, but disturbed. HAMA seems to be too soft -> exposure time too short
next steps: Increase T3 exposure time 25 s -> 35 s. Print 6x models.

comment: Vol. T1: 600 µL (layer 1), +50 µL (layer 3). Vol. T3: 400 µL (layer 2). Ca. 4 mm air bubble leads to defect in 1/6 prints in layer 1. HAMA channels well-defined and robust, are straight and not disturbed by washing/dipping process. Constructs collected for analysis.
